content:
Thank you, Mayank Agarwal and Krish Naik. The overall course has provided me with a profound knowledge of Big Data Engineering. Your effort and simple analogy to understand concepts and processes are absolutely amazing, especially how you relate them to our real-life situations. While doing this course, I noticed some issues in some lectures; unfortunately, I didn't note them down to share with you. But I remember one thing: while we were using Azure Synapse and creating the first external table, you didn't create a gold schema. I understand you forgot to take a video of that, or you may have skipped. I successfully completed the course, now applying to jobs and preparing for the interviews. For the final project, I have done my version of that, just asked LLMs how in industry things will happen and did according. course_name: Building Gen AI App 12+ Hands-on Projects with Gemini Pro
content:
As someone with experience in data science, I can see that Krish is extremely knowledgeable. I truly appreciate your effort, attitude, and enthusiasm towards teaching. I’ve followed some of your YouTube content and really value your goodwill in sharing your knowledge. However, I feel that this course could benefit from more structure to better align with the depth of your expertise.

While you clearly understand the material, the delivery often feels unorganized. It seems like the lessons were recorded without a clear script, leading to a lack of focus on which points need to be addressed and in what sequence. As a result, explanations sometimes become vague, and key concepts can get lost amidst repetition. This makes the videos lengthy, and despite the time invested, the core ideas don’t always come through as clearly as they should.

Along with all of your courses, I purchased and went through all other bestselling courses on Machine Learning and Deep Learning. Unfortunately, I felt that this course falls short in terms of preparation, clarity, and explanation compared to others.

More concise explanations and better preparation before each session would significantly improve the learning experience, helping students grasp the material more easily.

I genuinely admire your passion for teaching, and I believe that with some refinement, this course has the potential to be much stronger. Wishing you continued success, and I hope this feedback helps improve future iterations of the course.
clean_content: as someone with experience in data science i can see that krish is extremely knowledgeable i truly appreciate your effort attitude and enthusiasm towards teaching ive followed some of your youtube content and really value your goodwill in sharing your knowledge however i feel that this course could benefit from more structure to better align with the depth of your expertise while you clearly understand the material the delivery often feels unorganized it seems like the lessons were recorded without a clear script leading to a lack of focus on which points need to be addressed and in what sequence as a result explanations sometimes become vague and key concepts can get lost amidst repetition this makes the videos lengthy and despite the time invested the core ideas dont always come through as clearly as they should along with all of your courses i purchased and went through all other bestselling courses on machine learning and deep learning unfortunately i felt that this course falls short in terms of preparation clarity and explanation compared to others more concise explanations and better preparation before each session would significantly improve the learning experience helping students grasp the material more easily i genuinely admire your passion for teaching and i believe that with some refinement this course has the potential to be much stronger wishing you continued success and i hope this feedback helps improve future iterations of the course

course_name: Building Gen AI App 12+ Hands-on Projects with Gemini Pro
content: The videos in this course are available for free on his YouTube channel. If the videos are already accessible for free on the YouTube channel, I don't understand the purpose behind creating this Udemy course. Anyway, if you only want to build Gen AI apps, you can watch his YouTube playlist; there's no need to buy this course. The course should delve deeper into the basic concepts of Gen AI, but I can't say more since the title of the course specifies Gen AI apps only, so the main focus of this course is just building different apps. We can't claim that these projects are end-to-end, as the LLMOPS part is not covered in this course. I don't know why Sir has mentioned end-to-end projects. So, overall, it's the same as the YouTube videos, which are already available for free, so you'd have to spend your money purchasing this course. I expected that since it is Krish Sir's first Udemy course, it would be something new, but it's not.

course_name: Complete Agentic AI Bootcamp With LangGraph and Langchain
content:
I took this course to get a structured, end-to-end introduction to building agentic AI systems with LangGraph and LangChain, and it does a good job covering both the concepts and the practical implementation. It starts from the fundamentals of agentic AI and gradually moves into building real workflows, single-agent and multi-agent systems, memory, tools, and RAG-style applications. The course is long and detailed, and if you follow along, you come away with a solid understanding of how these frameworks are actually used in practice.

The main tradeoff is that the pacing can sometimes feel slow or repetitive, and some sections go deeper into setup or code mechanics than strictly necessary, while a few advanced topics (like deployment or more production-level patterns) could be expanded further. That said, for developers who want a thorough, step-by-step path into LangGraph-based agent systems and don’t mind a very detailed, classroom-style approach, this is a strong and useful course.

Complete Agentic AI Bootcamp With LangGraph and Langchain
content:
Krish has put in a tremendous amount of effort in designing the curriculum and explaining the topics step by step. The course is well-structured and easy to follow, which makes learning enjoyable. I really appreciate the clarity and logical flow throughout the sessions.
That said, there are a few areas where improvements could make this course even better:

At some instances, more practical and relatable examples could have been used to strengthen understanding.
The final projects could have emphasized advanced concepts like memory chains, retrievers, and other tools—perhaps building a full-fledged chatbot as a capstone project.
In certain sections, Krish seemed to run through the code quickly; a bit more in-depth explanation of the underlying logic would have added great value.

Overall, it’s a very good course and I learned a lot. Thank you, Krish, for your hard work and dedication!

The instructor appeared to be knowledgeable and competent, clearly explaining even the more complex concepts. However, I encountered a significant issue with the instructor’s keyboard usage—there were numerous typos that were not corrected, which unfortunately made some parts of the course difficult to follow and slightly frustrating.
Despite this drawback, I believe the course offers solid educational value, and I would recommend it to others interested in the topic. I hope future updates will improve the quality of the written material.

I mean there is not a single doubt on the fact that he offers absolutely flawless references and stuff, in fact he also uses free LLM provider like Ollama often but using OpenAI becomes a bit problematic for us to cope with. Rest assured his courses are just way too perfect for you to gather knowledge.
Go for it!!

content:
The pacing was too fast, especially for technical topics like DAX and Power BI where concepts build on each other. Some videos were cut while the training is going on and there was no continuation. Sometimes the trainers incoherent. Training has files which needed to be downloaded per lecture which is quite cumbersome. A simple link to github for us to get this files at once would have been fair..

The course so far has some repetitions. Section 23 covers what already been discussed from Section 17-21. 
• 	Python setup wasn’t explained, which is a major barrier — installation is the first hurdle, and if that’s unclear, everything else collapses.
• 	The instructors focused on delivering 580 plus slides instead of learning, which leaves you watching rather than understanding.
• 	My expectations weren’t met, especially since I bought this course to learn, not to be overwhelmed.

If you have no prior experience in SQL, DAX this training will leave you questioning your sanity. I am currently focusing only of Power BI tutorials and projecs. 

I am unsure if this trainin will equip me with the right skills to get a jobs as a Data Analyst

course_name: Complete Data Analyst Bootcamp From Basics To Advanced
content:
I joined this course expecting consistent teaching quality like Krish Naik’s sessions — which were clear, structured, and easy to follow. Unfortunately, when Jayant Topani took over, the experience dropped drastically. His explanations are confusing, the structure is missing, and the delivery feels unprepared. The sessions often go off-track, and you end up learning very little.
If you’re considering this course mainly because of Krish Naik, please note that not all instructors maintain that same standard. I wish I had known this before enrolling.

content:
🚀 Overall Experience:
The course provides an excellent foundation for mastering data analysis, covering Python, SQL, Power BI, and cloud technologies like Snowflake and AWS. It delivers well-structured content that balances theory with hands-on practice.

✅ What I Liked:

Comprehensive Curriculum – Covers Python, SQL, Power BI, and Cloud (AWS & Snowflake), making it well-rounded for aspiring data professionals.

Practical Approach – Great emphasis on real-world projects and hands-on exercises.

Clear Explanations – Concepts like EDA, Feature Engineering, and Statistical Analysis are explained in a way that is easy to follow.

Great for Beginners & Intermediate Learners – The course gradually builds up complexity, making it suitable for different levels.

📌 Areas for Improvement:

Could include more case studies related to real-world business problems to make it even more applicable.

Some topics on AWS & Snowflake could be expanded with more hands-on labs for better cloud integration practice.

💡 Final Thoughts:
This course is a great investment for anyone looking to excel in data analysis, whether for career growth or personal skill enhancement. Highly recommended for aspiring Data Analysts & Data Scientists! ⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐

content:
I really wanted to love this course, but I’m honestly disappointed. The instructor moves way too fast and doesn’t take the time to explain concepts clearly. It’s definitely not beginner-friendly, even though it’s advertised as such. I completed the first part of the course and still don’t understand what’s going on.

The lessons feel rushed, and the explanations are often unclear—especially when trying to follow along with coding. The instructor also has a heavy accent, which makes it even harder to keep up when everything is moving so quickly.

Overall, this course left me more frustrated and confused than confident. If you’re a true beginner hoping to understand data science step-by-step, this might not be the right fit. I really hope the instructor slows down and explains things more thoroughly in future updates.

course_name: Complete Data Science, Machine Learning, DL, NLP Bootcamp
content:
I'm really disappointed with this course. The explanations feel rushed, unclear, and lack proper depth. Important concepts are either skipped or explained so poorly that it becomes frustrating to keep up, even after just a few modules.

Many topics are simply skimmed over, as if the learner already knows them—which makes no sense, especially since this course is meant for beginners. It leaves you confused and constantly needing to look things up elsewhere.

It also seems like Krish Naik has just compiled videos from his YouTube channel and possibly reused content from other platforms where he’s taught before. For a paid course, this kind of recycled and disorganized content is just not acceptable and very unprofessional.

What’s worse is that many free YouTube videos from other instructors actually show much more effort and sincerity in breaking down complex topics. This course, on the other hand, feels like a half-hearted attempt that doesn’t live up to expectations. Honestly, I ended up learning most of the important concepts through textbooks and other online resources rather than from this course.

course_name: Complete Data Science, Machine Learning, DL, NLP Bootcamp
content:
I recently completed Krish Naik’s Data Science course on Udemy, and I must say it exceeded all my expectations. As someone who comes from a non-technical background, I was initially overwhelmed by the complexity of Data Science, but Krish's teaching style made everything so much easier to understand.

Krish Naik is not just an instructor he's a mentor. He breaks down complex concepts into simple, practical steps and always backs theory with hands-on coding and real-world use cases. What I appreciated the most was how he focused on both foundations (Python, statistics, ML algorithms) and industry projects, giving me confidence to apply what I learned in real scenarios.

The course content is very well-structured and up-to-date with the latest trends in the industry. Whether it’s data preprocessing, model training, or deploying ML models every topic is explained with clarity and depth.

If you're serious about building a career in Data Science, I highly recommend this course. Thank you, Krish Naik, for sharing your expertise and making Data Science approachable and exciting!

Complete Data Science, Machine Learning, DL, NLP Bootcamp
content:
Honest Course Review – What Worked Well & What Could Be Better

What I Liked:
1. The sections on Python and Supervised Machine Learning were well-structured and easy to follow.
2. ANN (Artificial Neural Networks) in the Deep Learning section was explained clearly and made the concept approachable.
3. The math explanations were done just right — focusing on what’s essential without going deep into lengthy derivations. That really helped keep the pace up.
4. NLP was also covered quite well, with decent clarity on foundational concepts.

What Could Be Improved:
1. The word “probably” was used a lot throughout the explanations. Since the subjects already involve probability and statistics, this made some parts feel a bit uncertain or repetitive. Using it more selectively would make the delivery stronger and more confident.
2. The Unsupervised Learning topics didn’t get the same level of attention or clarity as the Supervised ones. The explanation style here felt less confident and a bit rushed.
3. In the Deep Learning section, advanced topics like CNN, RNN, LSTM, GRU were not explained very well. I found them a bit confusing, and honestly, external blogs provided better clarity. The examples used didn’t always connect well, but with the strong basics from earlier sections, these topics can still be self-learned afterward.
4. There were no quizzes, assignments, or case studies to practice the ML, DL concepts. 

Final Thoughts:
I took this course as a crash course to quickly refresh and reinforce core AI/ML concepts without spending too much time searching all over the internet. For a beginner-level course at this price, it gives a solid bird’s-eye view of the field and builds a good foundation.

It took 4 months for me to finish this completely — though since I’m not a complete beginner, I could move faster. For someone entirely new to these topics, it might take a bit longer to get through everything comfortably.

Beginner Tip: Don't focus/stress too much on the Deployment part in the beginning, first get comfortable with EDA, Feature Engineering, Modelling, HyperParameter Tuning, Evaluation. Once you get comfortable with this then jump to MLOps as a separate topic for deployment.

course_name: Complete Data Science, Machine Learning, DL, NLP Bootcamp
Complete Data Science, Machine Learning, DL, NLP Bootcamp
content:
This course has been one of the most complete and enriching learning experiences I’ve taken in the field of data science. It combines deep theoretical foundations — including the mathematical intuition behind many algorithms — with hands-on code-along sessions that push you to apply what you’re learning.

What I appreciated most was the way Krish explains theory: he uses a digital notebook-style blackboard, writing and walking through each concept step by step — almost like attending a university lecture. This approach is used specifically during theoretical explanations, and helps make complex ideas more digestible before transitioning to hands-on coding separately.

What sets this course apart is how it doesn’t stop at model training. It extends into deployment and MLOps, which are often overlooked but critical skills for building real-world ML systems.

Some sections may feel dense if you’re not already familiar with the core ideas, but I see that as part of the challenge and growth. It’s a course that respects the learner and expects you to engage deeply.

content:
I really liked the way he taught everything, he even repeated some topics so that after listening to it again and again we get the points that we might i missed earlier.
But one thing is that there were some gaps in it, I understand that everything cannot be taught in great depth but still I would have loved a greater depth in this with all the mathematics needed, like exactly how backpropagation works for LSTM, transformers etc.
The practical implementations are also really good with deployment and all, just keep the content a bit updated as AWS has changed a bit, but the ML and DL part was really great.
Over all this course is worth it and if you not looking for mathematical intuitions, to become a researcher, this is a really good course to start with.

course_name: Complete Data Science, Machine Learning, DL, NLP Bootcamp
Complete Data Science, Machine Learning, DL, NLP Bootcamp
content: While I would like to give a 5 star rating for covering all the important topics, this course lacks the patience to explain the details that are required for a beginner in the field. If you have the mental energy to read between the lines and fill the gaps in the course, you can still complete. Else, this course is a bit difficult. It also looks like some videos posted here in the course are brought from another course elsewhere as the instructor keeps mentioning that there was a certain concept discussed earlier which was never discussed in the first place. Instructor misrepresents and misuses mathematical notations such as using eta for epsilon and epsilon for eta. I mean such mistakes are a no brainer and someone who has an attention to detail would not find it pleasing (which is a basic skill for a data scientist). I would second with the courses posted by Jose Portilla who explains concepts in a much better way and easy to follow along. Overall it is such a shame that this course despite of the great potential it had, is one among the falling stars.

course_name: Complete Data Science, Machine Learning, DL, NLP Bootcamp
content:
This course is truly an eye-opener for anyone wanting to dive into the world of Data Science, Machine Learning, Deep Learning, and Natural Language Processing. It covers everything from the basics to advanced concepts, offering both depth and clarity in a way that's easy to follow. The real value lies in the way complex topics are explained simply, making them accessible to learners at all levels.

The hands-on exercises and practical examples are what really set this course apart. Instead of just theory, you actually get to work with the concepts, which makes everything stick. The opportunity to apply what you're learning in real-time is invaluable and helps reinforce the lessons in a way that just reading about them can’t.

What makes this course even better is Krish’s teaching style. He's got a way of breaking down tough topics into bite-sized, understandable pieces, all while keeping things fun and interactive. He genuinely engages with everyone, making sure no one falls behind and everyone stays motivated throughout the course.

If you’re looking to get into Data Science, ML, DL, or NLP, or just want to level up your skills, this course is absolutely worth your time. Whether you’re a beginner or someone with some experience, you'll walk away with a deeper understanding and practical skills that you can immediately apply.

content: I’ve been following Krish Naik for over three years, but this course was honestly disappointing. The explanations feel rushed and lack depth. He moves through topics so quickly that it’s hard to keep up, and the teaching style doesn’t feel beginner-friendly at all.  Most of the videos seem to be reused directly from his YouTube channel, there’s no new content, no new projects, and nothing exclusive to the course. I basically ended up paying for free content that’s already available on his own channel.  While it’s impressive to see over 100 hours of video material, the overall structure and delivery really need improvement. The topics are rushed, the concepts are not explained clearly, and the course doesn’t offer anything fresh or well-organized.  If you’re thinking about buying it, I’d honestly recommend checking out his YouTube channel first everything in this course is already there for free. Save your money.

course_name: Complete Data Science, Machine Learning, DL, NLP Bootcamp
content:
I had an excellent experience with this course! The content was well-structured, clear, and easy to follow. The instructor provided deep insights into Feature Engineering, EDA, traditional ML algorithms, making even complex concepts like Neural networks and advance NLP topics understandable. I appreciated the practical examples and hands-on projects, which helped me apply what I learned in real-world scenarios.

Overall, this course exceeded my expectations and has significantly enhanced my skills in Data Science. Highly recommended for anyone looking to advance their knowledge in this field!

course_name: Complete Data Science, Machine Learning, DL, NLP Bootcamp
Complete Data Science, Machine Learning, DL, NLP Bootcamp
Complete Data Science, Machine Learning, DL, NLP Bootcamp
content:
Krish Naik sir did a fantastic job of explaining complex topics like machine learning algorithms, data visualization, and statistical analysis in an easy-to-understand manner. The practical exercises using Python were highly valuable, allowing me to apply what I learned immediately.

Pros:

1.Clear and concise explanations of concepts
2.Hands-on exercises and real-world projects
3.Good balance between theory and practical application
4.Accessible for both beginners and intermediate learners

Some sections, particularly on advanced topics like deep learning, could benefit from more in-depth coverage
It would be helpful to include more challenging projects for those looking to deepen their expertise.

Overall, this course has significantly improved my data science skills, and I feel much more confident in applying them to real-world problems. Highly recommend it to anyone looking to start or strengthen their knowledge in data science.

course_name: Complete Data Science, Machine Learning, DL, NLP Bootcamp
Complete Data Science, Machine Learning, DL, NLP Bootcamp
content:
As a data science practitioner, I find the course content to be well-structured. However, the quality of the material provided is lacking. The explanations are often inconsistent and lack clarity, particularly for many algorithms. In several instances, I've found the explanations to be incorrect. For example, the explanation of the Gradient Boosting Regressor is below standard and contains inaccuracies. By comparing it with the content on the StatQuest YouTube channel, the difference becomes evident. This is just one of the instances I am highlighting but there are other inaccuracies as well.

A note to learners: Do not rely solely on these lectures. It is advisable to consult additional resources to solidify your understanding of the concepts.

course_name: Complete Data Science, Machine Learning, DL, NLP Bootcamp
content:
As someone with experience in data science, I can see that Krish is extremely knowledgeable. I truly appreciate your effort, attitude, and enthusiasm towards teaching. I’ve followed some of your YouTube content and really value your goodwill in sharing your knowledge. However, I feel that this course could benefit from more structure to better align with the depth of your expertise.

While you clearly understand the material, the delivery often feels unorganized. It seems like the lessons were recorded without a clear script, leading to a lack of focus on which points need to be addressed and in what sequence. As a result, explanations sometimes become vague, and key concepts can get lost amidst repetition. This makes the videos lengthy, and despite the time invested, the core ideas don’t always come through as clearly as they should.

Along with all of your courses, I purchased and went through all other bestselling courses on Machine Learning and Deep Learning. Unfortunately, I felt that this course falls short in terms of preparation, clarity, and explanation compared to others.

More concise explanations and better preparation before each session would significantly improve the learning experience, helping students grasp the material more easily.

I genuinely admire your passion for teaching, and I believe that with some refinement, this course has the potential to be much stronger. Wishing you continued success, and I hope this feedback helps improve future iterations of the course.

Overall, it’s a good starter course for beginners.

content:
I'm extremely disappointed with this course I've been taking. The instructor's teaching method is basically copying and typing code from somewhere without any proper explanation. It's like they're just reading out comments and code in different English styles, calling it an explanation. Most of the videos feel like a waste of time.

What's frustrating is that the course structure is all over the place. For instance, Section 30 covers a basic RAG application that was already discussed in Section 28 and before. It's like they just uploaded random YouTube videos and called it a course. The course tries to cover too many topics but barely scratches the surface of each, leaving me feeling like I'm not getting the depth I paid for.

To make matters worse, the course doesn't seem to be designed for practical implementation. It's more like a money-making scheme than a serious educational resource. I expect a course to be well-organized, informative, and taught by someone who actually knows what they're doing.
If you're considering taking this course, I'd advise you to think twice. Unless you're looking for a basic overview, you might find it lacking in substance and value.

content:
**SCRAP this course, yaar! This is straight-up insult to your brain and wallet.**

I bought this course for ₹399 thinking I’ll get a tight, focused Generative AI training. What do I get?  Python stretching for hours ok this is good  — Then suddenly, out of nowhere, comes NLP, then deep learning, ML, ANN, RNN… like a big random salad with no taste or direction.

Where’s the roadmap? Where’s the structure? This guy just throws everything at you and says, “Learn it!” But *why* now? *Where* does it fit in the bigger picture of Generative AI? Nothing is organized, nothing flows. You’ll waste hours in stuff you don’t even need at that moment.

And the worst part? The actual Generative AI content starts at **lecture 113!** By then, you’ll already be so fed up, you won’t care anymore. It’s like buying a ticket for a movie and the main hero appears after 2 hours of boring side stories.

The instructor keeps repeating basics but no order he says what he remembers at that time  just surface-level theory, jumping from one topic to another like a confused puppy.

The course title screams “Complete Guide to Building, Deploying, and Optimizing Generative AI with Langchain and Huggingface,” but the reality? It’s scattered, messy, and incomplete. Important things are missing or barely touched.

If you want serious Generative AI knowledge, look elsewhere. This course is like a rotten mango — looks okay from outside, but inside, it’s spoiled.

Check the negative reviews, they’re not lying. Don’t be a fool like me. Save your money, save your time, save your sanity. You’ll regret wasting your energy on this hot mess.

course_name: Complete Generative AI Course With Langchain and Huggingface
content:
I took this course looking for a solid foundation in Generative AI, and while it delivers great content on LLM-based systems, it's important to be clear about what it doesn’t cover.

The practical sections using LangChain and Hugging Face are useful and relevant, especially for those interested in RAG pipelines or building chatbot-like applications.

However, given the title, I expected a broader exploration of Generative AI — maybe some coverage of image generation, text-to-speech, or even basic GANs. None of that is included. This course is really centered around text-based systems and large language models. That’s not a flaw in itself, but it’s something to be aware of if you’re looking for a more complete view of the GenAI landscape.

course_name: Complete Generative AI Course With Langchain and Huggingface
content:
For me the most useful part of this course was the LangChain introduction and some of the projects. I learned new interesting things about streamlit and langchain.
The course is not structured well, it starts with python basics (most of which you wont need later), then completely skips ANN and jumps into mathematical background of RNN. 
The theory behind the models are detailed, but a bit boring. The projects are almost the same, and really simple. 
As for the author, I don't really like his presentation skills: overusing filler words, randomly shouting. As for teaching, he doesn't really explain the logic behind the code, just reads out loud what he is writing. A lot of time is wasted by reading the models output and irrelevant things. Also, there are no coding tests where students could test their knowledge.

content:
I recently completed the Generative AI course by Krish Naik, and it was an outstanding learning experience! Krish Sir has a talent for breaking down complex AI concepts into simple, easy-to-understand explanations. The course covers everything from foundational generative models to advanced topics like Large Language Models (LLMs) and LLMOps, with practical, hands-on projects that reinforce learning.

I also explored Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG) separately, and Krish Sir’s teaching style made it easier to understand and apply these concepts in real-world scenarios. His structured approach—clear explanations, real-world applications, and practical coding sessions—makes the learning journey smooth and engaging. content:
I am writing to express my super serious dissatisfaction with this course, which has unfortunately been the worst I have encountered in terms of content accuracy and support.

    Nonexistent Support: I have posted questions six or seven times in the forum, only to be met with silence. The one response I received was over 11 days ago and offered nothing concrete beyond a vague “wait.” This level of disregard for student inquiries is completely unacceptable.



    Inaccurate and Misleading Content: The course materials are poorly constructed, for example in videos 74-80, which focus on creating a sentiment analysis model. The model you present is fundamentally flawed; it incorrectly gives high positive sentiment scores to feedback containing explicitly negative words like “scary” and “poor.” Such an error is inexcusable in a course claiming to teach accurate model creation.



    Unprofessional Response by Instructor: It is shocking that the instructor noticed this failure of the model but chose to laugh it off with a dismissive comment that the model “doesn’t care” about the sentence. This reaction is unprofessional and shows a lack of responsibility for teaching effective practices.



Frankly, this course has been a waste of time and resources, failing to meet basic standards of quality and support. I expect immediate steps to address these serious issues and ensure that future students do not encounter the same problems.

course_name: Complete Generative AI Course With Langchain and Huggingface
content:
If you're new to LangChain, I would recommend skipping this course. Having completed numerous courses on Udemy, I’ve noticed a common and effective pattern: instructors explain a concept and then demonstrate it with hands-on practice. Unfortunately, this course lacks that essential component.

Another issue is the absence of an incremental approach. A well-structured course typically starts with the basics and builds upon them progressively. However, in this course, each section feels like a standalone, pre-recorded video stitched together to create a sequence—lacking continuity.

Lastly, professionalism is crucial when creating paid content. The frequent typos in the videos were distracting and frustrating, and simply reading through hands-on code does not qualify as teaching. As paying customers, we expect a polished and engaging learning experience, which this course fails to deliver.

content:
Krishna,

Everything is great, but I'd like to offer one piece of feedback. The videos don't explain where the code comes from or where we can refer to for further clarification. For example, with Hybrid Search in Pinecone, I checked both the Langchain and Pinecone official documentation, but the code you provided doesn't align with what is in those sources, especially regarding dependencies.

It would be really helpful if you could share which documentation or resources you're drawing from so that we know where to look. This would help us build a deeper understanding rather than just memorizing the code.

Thank you again for all the valuable information!

course_name: Complete Generative AI Course With Langchain and Huggingface
Complete Generative AI Course With Langchain and Huggingface
content:
As someone with experience in data science, I can see that Krish is extremely knowledgeable. I truly appreciate your effort, attitude, and enthusiasm towards teaching. I’ve followed some of your YouTube content and really value your goodwill in sharing your knowledge. However, I feel that this course could benefit from more structure to better align with the depth of your expertise.

While you clearly understand the material, the delivery often feels unorganized. It seems like the lessons were recorded without a clear script, leading to a lack of focus on which points need to be addressed and in what sequence. As a result, explanations sometimes become vague, and key concepts can get lost amidst repetition. This makes the videos lengthy, and despite the time invested, the core ideas don’t always come through as clearly as they should.

Along with all of your courses, I purchased and went through all other bestselling courses on Machine Learning and Deep Learning. Unfortunately, I felt that this course falls short in terms of preparation, clarity, and explanation compared to others.

More concise explanations and better preparation before each session would significantly improve the learning experience, helping students grasp the material more easily.

I genuinely admire your passion for teaching, and I believe that with some refinement, this course has the potential to be much stronger. Wishing you continued success, and I hope this feedback helps improve future iterations of the course.

course_name: Complete Generative AI Course With Langchain and Huggingface
content: This course is more suited for those who prefer blindly following tutorials rather than truly understanding concepts. The instructor jumps between topics without properly explaining prerequisites or the thought process behind the code. While building chatbots with LangChain, Krish mostly copy-pastes code without clarifying how chains work or how to approach writing them, making it difficult to grasp the fundamentals. He skips theoretical explanations, which are crucial for understanding a framework like LangChain. Additionally, the course is outdated, still using LangChain v0.1 for agents despite its deprecation in favor of LangGraph. Overall, this course lacks depth and structure, making the official documentation a better learning resource.

content:
The Good:

You will walk out of this course with some really fantastic code.  I was particularly interested in the MLOps with ETL pipeline section - I was able to take the code that we made there and create a base repo for my future work after I renamed the package and centralized a few more settings.   I also got everything up and running in a self-hosted environment.  
Also, the instructor takes a lot of time to try to explain what he is doing.

The Not as Good

As others have noted, the instructor has some bad habits when it comes to verbal crutches.  For example, he probably has a habit of probably saying probably more times then he probably needs to.  
More importantly, while the instructor spends a lot of time talking about what we are working on, at times it is more of a code walkthrough.   For example the ETL / MLOps section is almost 8 hours, and it didn't need to be that long.  I get that there is a TON of great code to get to - it just seemed like there would have been more to deliver the lessons.   Also, some things (like setting up a project in github) didn't need to be covered over and over again.  The student can't always assume that they can skip those chapters because there might be something new buried in the 20 minute lesson (I found that out the hard way).  

Overall, I am very happy with what I got out of the course.

course_name: Complete MLOps Bootcamp With 10+ End To End ML Projects
content:
The material is good but the instructor has not answered any of the questions asked.
There are certain aspects that I would consider before enrolling in this course. Not a single question I have asked since starting this course has been answered by the instructor (I started in November 2024 and it is June 2025). This was the main reason I decided to take this course.
The instructor knows what he is doing and has a lot of knowledge but on some chapters it is almost as if you are reading the code by yourself. Some things are confusing, so I decided to ask questions but no one has answered them so far. Be warned about this.
Also there are parts of this course where the teacher says that he already explained some things, but they have not been explained. They must have to be from other of his courses because some things are not shown, especially on the Generative AI part.
Another minor inconvenience is that some files used in this course are not provided with a direct link via Udemy. I had to search them by myself on the instructor's repositories and since some file names had been modified it took more time than what I was expecting.

It would be better if the instructor at least gave the specific video link reference for the topics where he says that that was already covered. That way this would be more integrated and not feel as incomplete.

content: People who got this course at the beginning of their ML journey have no idea how lucky they are. Courses like this are so rare, here you get simple overview what ML engineering is all about in the REAL WORLD. Most of the courses focus on very low level stuff, go in depth of single topic what is huge overkill for most of the use cases at companies. Companies usually need simple but complete solution. No one cares if you can do CNN object detection model but only in Google Colab. This course will save you a lot of time, you won't be asking "how I actually do this, do that", here you have all you need to start working as ML. In fact this course should be first one you do right after understanding Python basics and libraries such as pandas, numpy, scikit, tensorflow (sequential model only) if you want to become MLE fast.

course_name: Complete Python With DSA Bootcamp + LEETCODE Exercises
content:
Undoubtedly one of the best DSA courses out there.

Mayank and Krish have done an outstanding job. What truly sets this course apart is the tutor’s deep commitment to clarity — he doesn’t just write code, he explains it again and again, even covering the tiniest details that most others assume you already know. That kind of patience and empathy for beginners is rare and absolutely commendable.

However, I’d like to humbly request the instructors to expand the course by adding a few core DSA topics that are currently missing. These are essential for interviews and problem-solving, and their inclusion would truly make this course a one-stop destination:

🔹 1. Arrays
Sorting: QuickSort, MergeSort

Searching: Binary Search

Two Pointers: e.g., remove duplicates, partitioning- not covered 

Sliding Window: subarray sums, min/max in windows -not covered

🔹 2. Linked Lists
Traversal

Insertion/Deletion at head, tail, position

Reversal (iterative + recursive)

Cycle Detection (Floyd’s Algorithm) -not covered we had just given a question to solve but havent practiced doubly linked list enough, can be improved

🔹 3. Hash Tables (Maps & Sets)
Concept of hashing

Lookup/Insert/Delete

Collision handling

🔹 4. Trees (BT & BST)
Inorder, Preorder, Postorder traversal

Recursive + Iterative approaches

BST Search, Insert -bfs and this not explained 

🔹 5. Stacks & Queues
Operations: Push/Pop/Peek, Enqueue/Dequeue

Applications in expressions, BFS, etc.

🔹 6. Heaps
Min/Max heap basics

Heapify & heap-building

Top-K problems using heaps

🔹 7. Graphs
BFS & DFS (both iterative and recursive)

Dijkstra’s Algorithm

Cycle detection (DFS)

🔹 8. Tries
Implement from scratch

Insert/Search/Prefix Matching

Autocomplete logic

🔹 9. Union-Find
Disjoint Set operations

Path compression, Union by rank

Graph cycle detection

🔹 10. Core Algorithm Techniques
Recursion: Base/recursive case, tree problems

Dynamic Programming: Memoization, Tabulation

Greedy Algorithms: Activity selection, coin problems

Backtracking: N-Queens, permutations, Sudoku  -not explained at all

Instead, I focused on conducting my own experiments with each topic, avoiding rote memorization. He understands that students should not simply act as "xerox machines," which I appreciate. Thank you, Krish !"

content:
I come from a commerce background and wanted to transition into the field of data science and analytics. Initially, I had doubts about whether I should enroll in this course, but I ultimately decided to take the leap—and now, I’m incredibly grateful for making one of the best decisions of my life.

This course covers everything required to become a data scientist or analyst. All the concepts are explained with real-world examples, which is one of the best aspects of this course. In school, we were never taught why we were studying specific topics, but here, Krish Sir breaks down complex ideas so simply that even a 5-year-old could understand them.

I’m especially thankful to Krish Sir for creating this course at such an affordable price (it costs less than a medium-sized pizza!).

If you’re serious about gaining a strong understanding of how math and statistics work in data science, I highly recommend enrolling in this course.

Thank you again, Krish Sir, for putting together this wonderful course!

course_name: Mathematics-Basics to Advanced for Data Science And GenAI
content:
I am currently taking the "Mathematics for Data Science" course by Krish Naik on Udemy, and I am thoroughly impressed with the quality and depth of the content. Even though I haven’t completed the course yet, I can already see the value it offers.

Content Coverage
So far, the course has provided a solid introduction to the mathematical concepts that are foundational to data science, such as linear algebra, calculus, and probability. Krish Naik does an excellent job of presenting these topics in a way that is both comprehensive and accessible.

Teaching Style
One of the aspects I appreciate most is Krish's teaching style. He uses straightforward, real-world examples to illustrate complex mathematical ideas, making them much easier to understand. His explanations are clear and concise, and he avoids overwhelming students with technical jargon.

Course Structure
The course is well-organized, with each topic building logically on the previous one. The videos are long but interesting, which makes it easy to fit learning into my schedule. Although I haven’t finished the course yet, the structure so far has made it easy to follow and retain the information.

Practical Application
Even at this stage, the course has demonstrated a strong emphasis on practical application. Krish connects the mathematical concepts to real-world data science problems, helping me understand not just the theory, but how to apply it in practice.

Accessibility
I’ve found the course to be highly accessible. Krish has a talent for breaking down complex topics into simple, manageable parts, making the content approachable for learners at all levels. Even if you’re not strong in math, his explanations make it easier to grasp the key concepts.

Overall Impression
Overall, my experience with the "Mathematics for Data Science" course by Krish Naik has been very positive. It’s a well-rounded course that is helping me build a strong mathematical foundation for data science. I’m looking forward to completing the course and applying what I’ve learned to real-world data science projects. You deserve the 5 star rating.

course_name: Ultimate RAG Bootcamp Using Langchain,LangGraph
content:
I took this course to get a serious, end-to-end understanding of RAG systems and agentic workflows in the LangChain/LangGraph ecosystem, and in terms of technical depth and topic coverage it delivers a lot of value. It goes well beyond toy examples and explains core concepts like embeddings, vector stores, retrievers, chains, agents, and different architectures, and then shows how to actually implement them in code. If you already have decent Python skills, you come away with a much clearer mental model of how modern RAG and agent systems are structured and why certain design choices matter.

The tradeoff is that the course is dense and sometimes feels more like a deep technical workshop than a polished, streamlined tutorial: the pacing can be uneven, some notebooks and code paths feel a bit messy, and because the ecosystem evolves quickly, a few imports or APIs may need small adjustments. That said, for developers who want real technical depth and are willing to think, debug, and adapt along the way, this is a very strong course that genuinely builds your capability to design and implement RAG and agent-based systems.

content:
Content is good but delivery of the knowledge could have been simpler and engaging.
Also, I think if the phrases/ words like "go ahead", "at the end of the day", "specifically" were used way too unnecessarily thereby disrupted the flow of absorbing the knowledge being imparted and elongated the training duration.

Lastly, to reinforce the knowledge being transitioned it is suggested to use context specific vocabulary. Example: instead of saying "I'll write this pass that" better to say "I'll call this method and pass string as an argument".

Another example:
Chapter 30, around 13:30 the trainer says "...have my another thing.."? The biggest improvement that the trainer must bring in to use technical and contextual vocabulary.

Possibly, a better statement was, "I'll call XYZ method or AIMessage class", which is more relatable and technically aligned than saying, "...have my another thing that is called AIMessage".

course_name: Ultimate RAG Bootcamp Using Langchain,LangGraph
content:
The course gives a decent introduction to RAG, but I felt it could have been much better with more practical depth. Most examples are based on very small toy documents instead of real-world datasets, which limits the learning experience.

Another issue is that several sections seemed to reuse content from the his other courses (like LangGraph), sometimes even repeating the same concepts. This makes the course feel a bit recycled rather than a fresh, dedicated RAG course.

If you’re completely new to the topic, you’ll still get value from the explanations.
